
<p>The following is a translation from the December 1999 issue of <em>Asahi Graph</em> magazine. It has been slightly edited for clarity and readability. The interview is conducted by Tomoko Ishizuka.</p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" />



<p><strong>Gundam Revival</strong><br><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline">The World of Yoshiyuki Tomino</span></strong></p>



<p class="has-vivid-red-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-5f60ee6e786f238edfc9d81aa8426ef0">Yoshiyuki Tomino is a legend in the world of Japanese animation. He celebrated his 35th anniversary as a creator this year, and now he&#8217;s aiming to add yet another masterpiece to his repertoire. Twenty years have passed since the birth of <em>Mobile Suit Gundam</em>. <em>Turn A Gundam</em>, which is currently airing on Fuji TV, is an ambitious work that can be said to be Tomino&#8217;s own challenge to the existing worldview of <em>Gundam</em>. It&#8217;s about people who have forgotten about the existence of those living on the other side of the universe, and it involves the sudden appearance of mechanical dolls (mobile suits) in an idyllic countryside. Today we focus on his latest work, which is filled with unexpected things that overturn the conventional wisdom of robot animation.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large"><a href="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png"><img width="803" height="1023" data-attachment-id="10505" data-permalink="https://tsukinomayu.com/2023/09/09/asahi-graph-magazine-12-1999-interview-with-yoshiyuki-tomino/image-3-6/" data-orig-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png" data-orig-size="2720,3468" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="image-3" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=235" data-large-file="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=663" src="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=803" alt="" class="wp-image-10505" srcset="https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=803 803w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=1606 1606w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=118 118w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=235 235w, https://turnafeezy.files.wordpress.com/2023/09/image-3.png?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 803px) 100vw, 803px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><strong>Director Yoshiyuki Tomino discusses his new work.</strong> &#8220;I felt like I had touched the literary arts for the first time with <em>Turn</em> <em>A</em>, which began with a total denial and acceptance of <em>Gundam</em>.&#8221;</figcaption></figure></div>


