<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" />



<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> Director Tomino, you have returned to the <em>Gundam</em> series after a long hiatus with your latest work, <em>Turn A Gundam</em>. What is the significance of the &#8220;∀&#8221;?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> When I decided to start this project, I made it an absolute condition to completely deny all past <em>Gundam</em> series while also bringing them all together. I chose the name &#8220;Turn A Gundam&#8221; because it is both a new <em>Gundam</em> series as well as a return to its origins. The worldview of <em>Turn A</em> might seem different from previous <em>Gundam</em> series, but the fact is it combines all of those worldviews into one.</p>



<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> <em>Turn A </em>certainly gives a different impression than previous <em>Gundam</em> series. Were there any obstacles in creating this series?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> Actually, thanks to <em>Turn A</em>, I was able to experience the joy of creation again. What I mean is that making something you like is not the same as creating a new story on your own. People who make things are generally egoists, and conversely—only egoists can make things. In the case of manga and animation, the words &#8220;what I like&#8221; and &#8220;my individuality&#8221; are deceiving. In fact, we often create stories within our own narrow worldviews to begin with. So in the case of animation, original works are always necessary. In other words, in a broad sense, it&#8217;s usually impossible to create a work without including elements of the writer&#8217;s own personality.</p>



<p>For the past fifteen years, I questioned whether or not I could call myself a writer. But this time, after trying to make a work on the premise of complete denial and affirmation, I realized that I really am not a writer. So when creating <em>Turn A</em>, I took a new approach. I asked several staff members to write some scenarios within the constraints of an overall plot structure, which naturally led to more detailed discussions. Of course, there were some people who didn&#8217;t want to deny nor affirm the former works in the way that was proposed, so there was a clash in ideology. Eventually, I gave the order to create a story that touched on the meaning of &#8220;∀&#8221;. I didn&#8217;t have time to write the entire plot myself. On top of that, the storytelling technique would&#8217;ve been too narrow if it was written by someone with no writing talent, so that&#8217;s why I chose not to write it by myself.</p>



<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> So during production, you had others write the initial scenario, and then you made additional changes to further mature it?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> Yes, and after realizing these scenarios into animated form, I eventually reached a point where the &#8220;Gundam&#8221; title felt meaningless to me. I came to this realization by the 34th episode (episode #35 in the TV broadcast, since there was one compilation episode). I felt that was I able to do this by taking an approach that was different from what I had done before. Deny and affirm all the <em>Gundam</em> series. Then, distribute that plot into twenty-one or twenty-two minute episodes. I thought, &#8220;Oh, this is another way to make TV animation.&#8221; I felt like I had touched the literary arts for the first time.</p>



<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> Did this cause any internal conflicts for you? Specifically, where does this &#8220;literary art&#8221; appear?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> It all happens in my mind, so ordinary people probably won&#8217;t be able to see it on-screen. I can only tell myself, &#8220;This is what a good story is like&#8221;, or &#8220;This is what a novel is like&#8221;. Even if at the end of the day it&#8217;s just one episode of a TV series, like a book without a clear ending. I didn&#8217;t think I would have made it to the level where I thought &#8220;I&#8217;ll do this with anime!&#8221; By episode #34 (#35), we finally reached the point where they leave Earth for space. If you focus on the imagery alone, it looks like a standard robot anime, and I think it&#8217;s difficult for viewers to understand all the intricacies. However, for me this episode was amazing.</p>


