ssions of Loran, Kihel, and the others. The storyboard establishes the sequence of picture arrangements of the story, which the animators then use as a basis for their work. Director Tomino explains the importance of storyboards, saying &#8220;Most of the production is determined by the storyboard.&#8221;</figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> Was it your goal to be able to express your anime as a literary work?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> I have always wanted to make live-action films, and I&#8217;ve always admired literary creations. <em>Gundam</em> is said to have set the standard for how to make robot anime. But if you continue using that same format for fifteen years, it becomes questionable if you can create new long-lasting works that stand the test of time. I realized that I would never learn how to create such works unless I actually tried to do so myself. If there&#8217;s only one role left for me, then it is my responsibility to create something that can serve as a guide. I tried with <em>Turn A</em> and thought &#8220;Oh, maybe I can do this!&#8221; </p>



<p>I also don&#8217;t think many people would come up with the idea of starting with a large conceptual story, like denying or affirming an entire TV franchise. This series makes an effort to never touch an arrangement theory. If I tried to approach the work as an arrangement, I knew I would fail. I already have professional intuition, and for the first time in twenty years that intuition kicked in. Working on a TV series like this has made me realize that <em>Turn A</em> is definitely not a continuous job for me. That&#8217;s why the meaning and significance I can put into it is substantial. I think I&#8217;ve been able to illustrate the idea that in the future, even if everyone were to make every part of an entire anime, down to the storyboards, that there would still be things to keep in mind. In any case, <em>Turn A</em> is completely different.</p>



<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> What exactly is the difference?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> For example, there are settings that are typical to science fiction or robot anime, but this time I took the stage to World War I. I also did it without using common tropes like time travel. Also, the distinction between ally and enemy remains unclear, and I make no attempt to clarify it in a single story plotline. In particular, with episodes #34 (35) and #26 (27) I think I was able to show the structure of the story itself, rather than just a battle. Maybe it&#8217;s due to my age, but I felt that these episodes were finished with a literary taste. The same could be said of the first two episodes&#8230; </p>



<p><strong>Ishizuka:</strong> I was surprised by the idyllic rural scenery in the first two episodes. Even the design work has changed, hasn&#8217;t it?</p>



<p><strong>Tomino:</strong> In terms of production, bringing on Syd Mead as the mechanical designer was a major factor. In the twenty years I&#8217;ve worked on <em>Gundam</em>, I&#8217;ve had various designers arrange the characters, but they always felt like arrangements instead of design. I told Bandai that if they were going to make a special series commemorating the 20th anniversary, that they should bring Syd Mead on board, and in the end they did. He has a brand name as a 1960s designer. When it comes to <em>Gundam</em> design, the style hasn&#8217;t differed much over the course of twenty years. I wondered what a 1960s designer with his level of foundational skill would be able to provide.</p>



<p>Akira Yasuda, who did the character design, initially wanted to enter the animation industry, but at this point he has been working in the video game industry for so long now. As a person with such a tenured background, he brings a brand new perspective. When I first approached him about the <em>Turn A</em> project, he said &#8220;Oh, that&#8217;s a good idea.&#8221; He also said, &#8220;When I saw the story of <em>Turn A</em>, I realized that this is the type of story I&#8217;ve wanted to see.&#8221; When I heard Yasuda say this, I realized there was something I wanted to tell young people: it doesn&#8217;t matter what you make, whether it is <em>Gundam</em>, robot anime, or science fiction, as long as you express it in your own individual way. It can be frustrating at times, but that&#8217;s what makes it &#8220;literary art&#8221;, isn&#8217;t it? If you don&#8217;t understand this part of literature, you can&#8217;t actually make robot or monster stories. I&#8217;ve finally reached the point that it feels wrong to create art without this mindset. It&#8217;s embarrassing to admit this at my age, but somebody needs to come out and say it. Otherwise we will continue to parrot things like &#8220;If you want to make a monster movie, just make something like <em>Godzilla</em>.&#8221; <em>Turn A</em> is my current proposal and response to that mentality.</p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" />



